{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_myrtle_ver01/data/56022775/00541313400/1949062701/0136.xml":{"full_text":"BRT Reaps Benefits on 4 Properties\nADA Calls for\nAction to Halt\nEconomy Slides\nCharles LaFollette,\nIndiana Liberal, Is\nAppointed Director\nWASHINGTON Ameri\ncans for Democratic Action\nswung into the battle for al\nleviating the dangerous tend\nencies toward recession in\nAmerican economy as a plan\nfor action was outlined at an\nexecutive board meeting, and\na liberal national director was\nnamed.\nA warning was sent President\nTruman and his Council of Eco\nnomic Advisors that it would be\n\u201cincredible folly\u201d if the nation\u2019s\nleaders avoided the \u201cdanger signs\u201d\nshowing that all is not well.\nCharles LaFollette, former lib\neral Republican congressman from\nIndiana, accepted the post of\nnational director, and will head\nADA\u2019s drive for membership and\nguide electoral activities.\nGets Unanimous OK\nTaking office July 1, his selection\nfor the job won unanimous ap\nproval from ADA executives. La\nFollette said he agrees with ADA\u2019s\npolicy of supporting progressive\nlegislators in both major parties.\nHe describes himself as an inde\npendent.\nHe resigned from a post as gov\nernor of Wuertemberg-Baden\u2014one\nof the three states in the Ameri\ncan Zone of Germany\u2014after\na\nclash with U. S. Commander Gen.\nLucius Clay over an increasingly\nanti-labor drift in policy. LaFol\nlette took the post after retiring\nfrom Congress in 1946, where he\nhad for four years supported pro\nlabor bills.\nPresident Truman and his eco\nnomic advisors were asked by ADA\nto \u201cInclude in their forthcoming\nmid-year report an\nunvarnished\nanalysis of the current economic\nsituation, without panic but also\nwithout sugar-coating. If an emer\ngency is found to exist, we urgently\nrequest that they present to Con\ngress\ncreasing\npower.\nrecommendations\nconsumer\nfor\nin\npurchasing\n\u201cA precise report on the present\nplans for public works and a time\nschedule stating how soon they\ncan be started should be included in\nsuch a report.\u201d\nADA called for immediate ac\ntion on:\nAn expanded 75-cent minimum\nwage.\nExtended and increased social\nsecurity benefits.\nA public housing program.\nFederal aid to education.\nThe Brannan farm program.\nA cut in consumer (excise)\nfaxes offset by higher personal\nand corporate income taxes on\nthose best able to pay more.\nBig Business could help, said\nthe ADA board, \u201cby making price\nand wage adjustments in high\nprofit industries.\u201d\n\u2018Pinky\u2019Lee Improves\nCHICAGO\u2014M. M. \u201cPinky\u201d Lee\n(832), popular Legal Aid investi\ngator who has been critically ill\nin Alexian Brothers Hospital here,\nshowed slight improvement during\nthe week but is still not allowed\nvisitors.\nMrs. Lee reported that his con\nprivate nurses\ndition\nrequires\naround the clock. She expressed\nthe family\u2019s appreciation for flow\ners and many letters and cards\nthat have poured in, but asks\nfriends to refrain from sending\nany more flowers since \u201cPinky\u2019s\u201d\nphysicians won\u2019t allow them in his\nroom.\nThe Lee residence is 215 Berry\nParkway, Park Ridge, Ill.\nANOTHER PILLAR FOR THE FAIR DEAL COLUMN\u2014\nCongressman Franklin D. Roosevelt Jr. chats with President Tru\nman soon after he was sworn in as member of the House of Rep\nresentatives from New York's 20th Congressional District. Young\nRoosevelt assured the President of his loyalty to the Democratic\nParty and the Fair Deal program.\n\nTil Continue to Work for a\nFair Deal,\u2019 Roosevelt Declares\nWASHINGTON\u2014\u201cI campaigned on the Fair Deal pro\ngram and I will continue to work in the cause of a fair deal.\u201d\nThose were the words of Congressman Franklin D.\nRoosevelt Jr., recently elected to represent New York\u2019s 20th\nDistrict in the House of Representatives, to J. M. (Jake)\nGordon, TRAINMAN NEWS correspondent and member of BRT\nPublic Relations Advisory Committee, shortly after he ac\ncepted the oath of office.\ni am interested at tne present\ntime in a long-range housing pro\ngram for low-income groups, health\ninsurance, increase of the minimum\nwage to at least 75 cents an hour,\nrepeal of the Taft-Hartley Law and\nenactment of legislation to\nen\ncourage the free labor movement,\u201d\nMr. Roosevelt said.\nActing Speaker John W. McCor\nmack administered the oath of\noffice to FDR Jr., who was accom\npanied by Rep. Walter A. Lynch\n(D-NY).\nMrs. Roosevelt Beams\nSeated in the President\u2019s gallery,\nMrs. Franklin D. Roosevelt beamed\nproudly as her son swore to uphold\nthe Constitution of the United\nStates.\nIncluded in her party of well\nwishers were former Gov. and Mrs.\nCharles Poletti,\nMr.\nand Mrs.\nHarry Rogers, Justice Benjamin\nRabin, New York State Supreme\nCourt; Murray Baron, New York\ncounty chairman of the Liberal\nParty; John Stillman, chairman,\nNew York State Americans for\nDemocratic Action Affairs Com\nmittee; Anthony B. Akers, a mem\nber of Mr. Roosevelt\u2019s law firm;\nMrs. Lillian de Sales, FDR Jr.\u2019s\nsecretary; J. M. Gordon and John\nLonigan of ECA, a friend of the\nnew congressman.\nAfter the ceremony, Congress\nman Roosevelt chatted with Presi\ndent Truman at the White House\nand pledged his loyalty to the Dem\nocratic Party and the Fair Deal\nprogram.\nin\nMany political figures and others\nthe national limelight were\namong the many persons who at\ntended a reception in Hotel Carl\nton, including Sen. Hubert Humph\nrey (Minn), Rep. A. J. Biemiller\n(Wise), Rep. John C. Davies (NY),\nRep. Helen Gahagan Douglas\n(Calif), Grace Tully, secretary to\nlate\nRoosevelt;\nthe\nPresident\nJames Loeb, executive secretary,\nnational ADA, and David Niles of\nthe White House staff.\n\u201cFrom the attention he received,\nmany political leaders view his\nfirst election to public office as a\npath to the executive mansion in\nAlbany and later to the White\nHouse in Washington,\u201d Gordon\ntold TRAINMAN NEWS.\n\u201cHistory does repeat itself some\ntimes and it could not happen to a\nnicer guy.\u201d\nOldsters Honored\nCHICAGO Henry Erick and\nCornelius E. McMillan, Lodge 4,\nreceived 55 and 50-year pins, re\nspectively, from General Secretary\nand Treasurer W. P. Kennedy re\ncently at a special dinner party.\nFollowing members with 45 or\nmembership\nmore\nyears\nwere\nguests of honor:\nA. M. Adams,\nS. E. Brenneman, E. J. Dwyer,\nW. G. Edens, Al Hultgren, T. E.\nKernan, J. P. Maloney, Lawrence\nMcManus, W. E. Minor, J. J. Oliver,\nC. W. Quick, Peter Tole and A. W.\nWeber.\nEd Rudin, field supervisor, was\nmaster of ceremonies and Vice\nPresidents W. M. Dolan, W. E. B.\nChase and S. Vander Hei were\npresent.\nMr. Kennedy spoke on BRT sta\ntistics and explained the railroad\npension board, reports S. P. Gat\ntone, publicity chairman.\nMany BRT-ers\nKeep Receipts\nTN Finds Out\nL. N. Wright, 40-year BRT\ner in Lodge 78, Los Angeles,\nisn't alone in his hobby of\nsaving monthly receipts.\nMany Brotherhood mem\nbers collect the slips, train\nman news has found out, and\ntwo more of them are E. W.\nPetrie and C. J. Boehner, both\n50-year members, of Lodges\n142, Meadville, Pa., and 254,\nLittle Falls, N. J., respec\ntively.\nPetrie has all his receipts during\nhis half-century membership,\naC\ncording to W. S. Allen, 142 local\nchairman on the Erie, who paid a\nvisit to trainman news June 20\u2014\nthe day he began his 33rd year on\nthe railroad.\nBoehner,\nonly living charter\nmember of 254, which was organ\nized Aug. 30, 1896, also has kept\nall his receipts during his more\nthan 50-year membership. He has\nheld every office in 254 at one time\nor another.\n\u201cI am very proud of my bunch of\nreceipts, as they bring back fond\nmemories of the BRT,\u201d Boehner\nsaid.\n\u201cThe BRT is a wonderful order\nto belong to\u2014we always have a\ngrand set of officers\nLodge.\u201d\nin Grand\nEighty-six-year-old J. Newton\nGross of Lodge 160, Philadel\nphia, has a collection which is\nreally something to crow about.\nHe\u2019s been in the Brotherhood 63\nyears and has his receipts for all\nthat time.\nHe was a delegate to the Denver\nconvention.\nThe oldtimer started railroading\non the Erie in 1892 and was pro\nmoted second class in 1897 and first\nclass five years later.\nHe was forced to retire in 1934\ndue to an injury to his right foot\nand \u201cwas awful sorry that I had\nto give up my railroading.\u201d\nA picture showing L. N. Wright\nwith 480 receipts he has saved dur\ning his 40 years in the Brotherhood\nwas carried on Page 8 of the June\n20, 1949 issue of trainman news.\nBLOOMINGTON, Ill.\u2014C. F. Sal\nmon, 30-year member of Lodge 62,\nwarns BRT-ers against commercial\ninsurance policies. His policy with\nthe Provident Life and\nAccident\nInsurance Company, Chattanooga,\nTenn., was cancelled by the com\npany after he had paid on it for\n10 years.\nConductor Smoky Joe\nClickety Bung Railrood\nPSALM OF THE NO-BILL\nThe members of the Brotherhood of Railroad Train\nmen are my fellow-employes; I shall not want. They\nimprove my working conditions, and I receive more\nof life\u2019s pleasures. Mypay is increased, with no thanks\nto myself. Yea; I rest while my fellow-employes toil in\nmy interest. I feel no evil; my fellow-employes protect\nme. Their labors comfort me. They see my needs as\nthey see their own. What they get, I get. Why should\nI worry?\nSurely ease and plenty will follow me all the days\nof my life, and I shall eat of the fruits of their labor\nforever.\n\n3NO-BILL\nPUBLIC OPINION\nRE6.UA PAT. 0.\n0 SMALL MOT WANT\nI\nEPMILLERO 1\nNew Southern\nPact Contains\nImprovements\nMen on Southern\nPacific, New York\nDock Also Winners\nBrotherhood members on\nfour railroads reaped a virtual\nharvest of better\nworking\nrules and other benefits thru\nnew\nagreements\nwon\nand\nclaims settled by their aggres\nsive grievance committees.\nProperties\ninvolved\nwere\nthe Southern Railway, South\nern Pacific Railroad (Pacific\nLines), New York Dock Rail\nway and Bush Terminal Rail\nroad.\nThirteen different\ncontaining:\nmany\nagreements,\nimprovements,\nwere obtained from the Southern.\nManagement displayed obstinacy\nthruout conferences with Brother\nhood representatives and offered\ncounter proposals whenever pos\nsible, but the BRT grievers.\nas\nsisted by Vice-President J. P. Ca\nhill, did not back down one step\nfrom their original demands.\nThe Brotherhood was preparing\nto take a strike vote when media\ntion was invoked. When a mediator\non the property failed in his mis\nsion, the full mediation board en\ntered the case and the agreement\nfollowed. It is effective July 1.\nCounter Proposals Futile\n\u201cThey (management) had ap\nproximately 45 counter proposals\nto our\nproposals,\" Vice-President\nCahill declared, \"and I am happy\nto report that they did not accom\nplish one point in all of their coun\nter proposals.\n\u201cWe were successful in signing\nthirteen\nagreements.\nseparate\nset\nup\nand\nin\ndistinct\nseparata\nbooks for all the yard and road\nmen on the Southern Railway Sys\ntem.\u201d\nAll the standaid\nrules\nmaintained in passenger\ni were\nservice\nand understandings reached both\nlocally and nationally.\nRules in freight\nservice\nwel 6\nbettered to\na\nyardmen\ngained\ngreat extent and\nnumerous\nim\nproved conditions.\nThe following railroads comprise\nthe Southern System:\nSouther n\nRailway, road and yard service;\nEast St. Louis\nTerminals, yard\nservice; St. Johns River Terminal,\nyard service; Cincinnati, New Or\nleans and Texas Pacific Railway,\nroad and yard service; Alabama\nGreat Southern Railroad, road and\nyard\nservice;\nNew\nNortheastern Railroad,\nOrleans\n\nroad and\nyard service; Georgia Southern\nFlorida Railway, road and yard\nservice, and New Orleans Terminal\nCompany, yard service.\nA back payroll of $34,000 in set\ntlement of claims for yardmen\u2019s\nrate of pay, in addition to earnings,\nwent to road crews\non\nWestern\nDistrict of the Western Division,\nSouthern Pacific.\nFurthermore, more than $1,000\nwas paid road trainmen on cur\nrent payrolls because of this set\ntlement.\nThere\u2019s\nGrievers Skillful\n\"peculiar\ntwist\" to\na\nthis settlement, according to Stan\nley B. Rider, publicity chairman of\nLodge 71, Oakland, Calif., which\nclearly shows, he says, the skill\npossessed by the\nBrotherhood\u2019s\ngrievers.\nHere\u2019s the \u201cbackground\" as re\nlated by Rider:\n\u201cThe original claim, which\nre\nsuited in this fine settlement, was\none made by a conductor, G. H.\nDanis (71), for local freight rate\naccount making three stops\nen\nroute to set out and pick up cars.\nThe division superintendent denied\nthe claim on the grounds that the\nset-outs and pick-ups on Danis\u2019\ntrain were made by yard crews.\nLodge 71 ordered the grievance\nwhich Danis made of the super\n(Continued on Page 6)","height":"20628","width":"14084"}}
